51
00:03:01,320 --> 00:03:04,320
The first two are probably the most important, and let's start with motivation.

52
00:03:04,980 --> 00:03:08,860
This actually has two meanings I can think of, one on the macro scale and one on the

53
00:03:08,860 --> 00:03:09,420
micro scale.

54
00:03:10,020 --> 00:03:15,040
By macro scale motivation, I mean how well do you hook someone into the lesson as a whole?

55
00:03:15,590 --> 00:03:20,240
This video by Alexander Berdnikov opens by asking why it is that when you hear a plane

56
00:03:20,240 --> 00:03:23,960
approaching the pitch of its sound seems to slowly fall.

57
00:03:24,660 --> 00:03:28,720
He points out how a lot of people assume that this is the Doppler effect, but that this

58
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:32,980
doesn't actually hold up to scrutiny, since for example that pitch actually rises as the

59
00:03:32,980 --> 00:03:34,100
plane is going away from you.

60
00:03:34,560 --> 00:03:37,580
It's a good point, and an interesting question, you have my attention.

61
00:03:38,640 --> 00:03:42,560
One of my favorite articles in the batch by Adi Mittal prompts you to wonder about an

