00:03:49,380 --> 00:03:53,820
the linear algebra and projective geometry involved in a DIY-style project to stitch

65
00:03:53,820 --> 00:03:57,080
together two overlapping images taken at different angles.

66
00:03:57,640 --> 00:04:01,200
Application and tangible problems can make for great motivation, but that's not the

67
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:02,340
only source of motivation.

68
00:04:02,900 --> 00:04:06,720
Depending on the target audience, a good nerd sniping question can also do the trick.

69
00:04:07,220 --> 00:04:11,560
This video on the channel Going Null opens with a seemingly impossible puzzle.

70
00:04:12,040 --> 00:04:16,900
10 prisoners are each given a hat, chosen arbitrarily from 10 total hat types available.

71
00:04:17,520 --> 00:04:21,480
It is possible for some of the prisoners to have the same hat type as others, and everyone

72
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:23,740
can see all of the other hats, but not their own.

73
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:28,500
After given a little time to look at everyone else's hat and think about it all, the prisoners

74
00:04:28,500 --> 00:04:31,920
are to simultaneously shout out a guess for their own hat type.

75
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:36,860
The question is, can you find a method that guarantees at least one of the prisoners will

76
00:04:36,860 --> 00:04:37,940
make a correct guess?

77
00:04:40,120 --> 00:04:45,640
This video by Eric Rowland motivates the idea of p-adic numbers and the p-adic metric by

78
00:04:45,640 --> 00:04:50,200
showing how if you take 2 to the 10th, and 2 to the 100th, 2 to the 1000th, so on and

79
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:55,380
so on, and you assign distinct colors to each digit, lining them all up on the right, you

80
00:04:55,380 --> 00:04:58,960
can see that their final digits line up more and more with larger powers.

81
00:04:59,880 --> 00:05:03,980
Then he asks the question of whether it's reasonable to interpret this as a kind of

82
00:05:03,980 --> 00:05:07,880
convergence, despite the fact that these numbers are clearly diverging to infinity

83
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:09,100
in the usual sense.

84
00:05:10,240 --> 00:05:14,680
A completely different form of motivation can come from showing the historical significance

85
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:18,340
of a problem or a field, in a sense giving the viewer a feeling that they're part of

86
00:05:18,340 --> 00:05:19,020
something bigger.

87
00:05:19,740 --> 00:05:24,440
One excellent video on a channel A Well-Rested Dog provides an overview of the history of

88
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:28,240
calculus and the progression of how some of the world's smartest minds grappled with

89
00:05:28,240 --> 00:05:30,560
the nuances of infinity and infinitesimals.

90
00:05:30,560 --> 00:05:34,620
It's the right mixture of entertaining and detailed, and he goes on to talk about how

91
00:05:34,620 --> 00:05:39,160
learning all of this made his own questions and confusions in a calculus class feel validated,

92
00:05:39,600 --> 00:05:41,460
which I think a lot of students can resonate with.

93
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:46,200
This example is less about the intro of a video motivating the lesson it teaches, and

94
00:05:46,200 --> 00:05:49,320
more about the entire video motivating an entire field.

95
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:54,720
Another one like that would be this lecture, by the channel Thisery, laying out how Cantor's

96
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:59,340
diagonalization argument and the halting problem and a number of other paradoxes people might

97
00:05:59,340 --> 00:06:03,940
have heard of in math, computer science, and logic all follow the same basic pattern.

98
00:06:04,340 --> 00:06:08,440
And moreover, if you try to formalize the exact sense in which they follow the same

99
00:06:08,440 --> 00:06:12,380
pattern, that ends up serving as a pretty nice motivation for the subject of category

100
00:06:12,380 --> 00:06:12,840
theory.

101
00:06:14,280 --> 00:06:18,600
And the last flavor of motivation I'll mention is if you can somehow make the learner feel

102
00:06:18,600 --> 00:06:20,620
like they're playing an active role in the lesson.

103
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:26,000
This is very hard to do with a video, maybe even impossible, and it's best suited for

104
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:26,980
in-person lessons.

105
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:31,600
But one written entry that I thought did this especially well was an inverse Turing test,

106
00:06:31,820 --> 00:06:35,640
where you as the reader are challenged to come up with a sequence of ones and zeros

107
00:06:35,640 --> 00:06:40,620
that appears random, and the article goes on to explain various statistical tests that

108
00:06:40,620 --> 00:06:44,960
you could apply to prove that the sequence was actually human-generated, and not really

109
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:45,380
random.

110
00:06:46,060 --> 00:06:50,480
The content of the article is centered around the particular sequence that you, the reader,

111
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:54,780
created, and you're invited to change it along the way to try to get it to pass more tests.

112
00:06:54,780 --> 00:06:58,920
It's a nice touch, and I could easily see this working really well as a classroom activity.

113
00:06:59,780 --> 00:07:03,420
Whatever approach you take, whatever flavor of motivation is your favorite, it's hard

114
00:07:03,420 --> 00:07:07,780
to overstate just how important it is that you do actually give viewers a reason to care.

115
00:07:08,260 --> 00:07:12,480
This is true for any piece of content, but I think it's especially true for educational

116
00:07:12,480 --> 00:07:17,400
content and even more so for math, given the amount of focus and thought that these topics

117
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:18,260
sometimes require.

118
00:07:19,140 --> 00:07:23,300
I think this was articulated best by the author of one of my favorite podcasts, An Opinionated

119
00:07:23,300 --> 00:07:27,680
History of Mathematics, who has a manifesto on his website that lays out what he calls

120
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:30,820
the axioms of learning, beginning with the first axiom,

121
00:07:31,460 --> 00:07:35,640
quote, In a perfect world, students pursue learning not because it is prescribed to them,

122
00:07:35,640 --> 00:07:38,480
but rather out of a genuine desire to figure things out.

123
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:43,360
It follows that we must not introduce any topic for which we cannot first convince the

124
00:07:43,360 --> 00:07:45,420
students that they should want to pursue it.

125
00:07:46,420 --> 00:07:51,660
That said, one mistake that I think I've made in past videos is to over-philosophize

126
00:07:51,660 --> 00:07:52,980
in the video's introduction.

127
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:57,800
Motivation is critical, but it doesn't have to take long, and often what actually keeps

128
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:01,620
the viewer engaged is to get right to the point and leave any commentary about broader

129
00:08:01,620 --> 00:08:03,240
themes and connections to the end.

130
00:08:03,820 --> 00:08:08,620
If you can, motivate using clear examples, not sweeping statements or promises of what

131
00:08:08,620 --> 00:08:09,280
is to come.

132
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:15,000
By microscale motivation, what I mean is whether each new idea that's introduced in the lesson

133
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,440
itself feels to the learner like it has a good reason to be there.

134
00:08:18,440 --> 00:08:23,260
For instance, this video by Joshua Maros gives a fairly detailed overview of ray tracing,

135
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:28,160
and what I love about it is that before he introduces any new technical topic, like the

136
00:08:28,160 --> 00:08:32,920
rendering equation, importance sampling, or the ReSTER algorithm, he's already outlined

137
00:08:32,920 --> 00:08:37,400
the main idea and intuition for that topic with really well-visualized examples.

138
00:08:37,780 --> 00:08:42,120
It makes it so that once the equation comes on the screen, or the algorithm is described,

139
00:08:42,260 --> 00:08:45,560
it doesn't feel like an expression handed down with nothing to hold onto.

140
00:08:46,080 --> 00:08:50,800
Instead, it arrives only once it's articulating something that already exists at least loosely

141
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:53,820
in the viewer's mind, making it much easier to parse.

142
00:08:54,980 --> 00:08:59,540
This video by Michael DeFranco about extending the factorial offers another great example

143
00:08:59,540 --> 00:09:01,560
of a lesson with good motivation along the way.

144
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:06,040
You may have heard that there's a function generalizing the factorial to real and even

145
00:09:06,040 --> 00:09:07,780
complex inputs, the gamma function.

146
00:09:08,260 --> 00:09:12,460
The usual definition is written down as a certain integral expression sort of handed

147
00:09:12,460 --> 00:09:17,660
down from on high, and the justification for why this generalizes factorials is certain

148
00:09:17,660 --> 00:09:19,320
properties that you can prove about it.

149
00:09:19,540 --> 00:09:21,600
But a lot of students find this unsatisfying.

150
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:22,680
Where does it come from?

151
00:09:23,280 --> 00:09:27,620
By contrast, in Michael's explanation, he starts by observing the properties that are

152
00:09:27,620 --> 00:09:32,060
true of the normal factorial function that you would want to be true of a general version,

153
00:09:32,580 --> 00:09:37,420
and uses those desired properties to motivate various different alternate expressions massaged

154
00:09:37,420 --> 00:09:42,400
here and there to be more amenable to non-whole-number inputs, ultimately leading to a pretty satisfying

155
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:42,860
answer.

156
00:09:44,100 --> 00:09:48,200
Another good template for this microscale motivation when introducing a pretty complicated

157
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:53,320
solution to a problem is to start with a naive but flawed solution, and then progressively

158
00:09:53,320 --> 00:09:54,140
refine it.

159
00:09:54,560 --> 00:09:59,000
This article by Max Slater on differential programming does this particularly well.

160
00:09:59,480 --> 00:10:04,320
The basic question is how you get computers to evaluate derivatives, a ubiquitous task

161
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:05,180
for machine learning.

162
00:10:05,820 --> 00:10:10,680
He starts by describing the most obvious approach, and then what flaws it has, and uses that

163
00:10:10,680 --> 00:10:12,520
as motivation for another approach.

164
00:10:13,020 --> 00:10:16,800
But that one has its own flaws, and fixing those motivates yet another approach, and

165
00:10:16,800 --> 00:10:17,460
so on.

166
00:10:17,800 --> 00:10:23,060
The ideas he builds up to, dual numbers and backward-mode automatic differentiation, both

167
00:10:23,060 --> 00:10:28,160
could feel a bit confusing if presented out of the blue, but in context, having motivated

168
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:32,500
each new idea by pointing out flaws with the previous ones, it all ends up feeling utterly

169
00:10:32,500 --> 00:10:33,020
reasonable.

170
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:37,660
Turning back to that same prisoner hat puzzle I referenced earlier, one of the other things

171
00:10:37,660 --> 00:10:41,360
I liked about it is how the author doesn't just present the solution, there are plenty

172
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:43,300
of puzzle videos out there which do that.

173
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:47,720
Instead, he gives a pretty authentic look at the wrong turns and tangents that are involved

174
00:10:47,720 --> 00:10:52,620
in the problem-solving process, not even eating up too much time to do so, and justifies each

175
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:55,020
new step with a general problem-solving principle.

176
00:10:55,760 --> 00:11:00,400
All of this microscale motivation could just as well be categorized as a subset of clarity.

177
00:11:00,860 --> 00:11:04,900
If motivating a lesson determines how much attention and focus the viewer is willing

178
00:11:04,900 --> 00:11:08,840
to give you, clarity determines how quickly you burn through that focus.

179
00:11:09,340 --> 00:11:13,000
The best hook in the world is wasted if the lesson which follows is confusing.

180
00:11:14,060 --> 00:11:18,700
This presentation by Xplanaria talks about how to describe various crystal structures

181
00:11:18,700 --> 00:11:24,220
using group theory, which, considering the complex 3D forms involved and the fact that

182
00:11:24,220 --> 00:11:27,640
most people don't know group theory, has the potential to be very confusing.

183
00:11:28,280 --> 00:11:32,800
But they do a really effective job at keeping concrete examples front and center, guiding

184
00:11:32,800 --> 00:11:37,080
the reader to focus on one relevant pattern at a time, and distilling down to a simple

185
00:11:37,080 --> 00:11:41,060
version of an idea before seeing how that fits into a broader, more general setting.

186
00:11:41,980 --> 00:11:46,700
In general, entries that struck me as especially clear would often keep one or two examples

187
00:11:46,700 --> 00:11:50,920
front and center, and they'd often give a feeling of playing with those examples, maybe

188
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:55,220
running simulations or tweaking them to run up against edge cases, and all around giving

189
00:11:55,220 --> 00:11:59,360
the viewer a chance to build their own intuitions before general rules are presented.

190
00:11:59,840 --> 00:12:02,540
The example doesn't even have to be explicit.

191
00:12:03,060 --> 00:12:07,540
In a visually driven lesson, the choice of what to show on screen when making general

192
00:12:07,540 --> 00:12:12,320
points is often a great opportunity to offer the viewer a concrete example to hold onto,

193
00:12:12,620 --> 00:12:16,920
but without wasting too much time explicitly talking about that example or overemphasizing

194
00:12:16,920 --> 00:12:17,640
its importance.

195
00:12:18,120 --> 00:12:22,140
This I think is part of what gives visually driven lessons the opportunity to be clearer.

